## Generics

### Generic Functions

```go
// Generic function with type parameter
func Max[T comparable](a, b T) T {
    if a > b {
        return a
    }
    return b
}

// Usage
maxInt := Max(10, 20)           // Type inferred
maxFloat := Max[float64](3.14, 2.71)  // Explicit type

// Multiple type parameters
func Swap[T, U any](a T, b U) (U, T) {
    return b, a
}

// Type constraints
type Number interface {
    int | int32 | int64 | float32 | float64
}

func Sum[T Number](numbers []T) T {
    var sum T
    for _, n := range numbers {
        sum += n
    }
    return sum
}

// Using standard constraints
import "golang.org/x/exp/constraints"

func Min[T constraints.Ordered](a, b T) T {
    if a < b {
        return a
    }
    return b
}
```

### Generic Types

```go
// Generic struct
type Stack[T any] struct {
    items []T
}

func (s *Stack[T]) Push(item T) {
    s.items = append(s.items, item)
}

func (s *Stack[T]) Pop() (T, bool) {
    var zero T
    if len(s.items) == 0 {
        return zero, false
    }
    item := s.items[len(s.items)-1]
    s.items = s.items[:len(s.items)-1]
    return item, true
}

// Usage
intStack := Stack[int]{}
intStack.Push(42)
value, ok := intStack.Pop()

// Generic interface
type Container[T any] interface {
    Add(T)
    Get(int) T
    Size() int
}

// Type inference with generics
type Pair[T, U any] struct {
    First  T
    Second U
}

// Constructor function
func NewPair[T, U any](first T, second U) Pair[T, U] {
    return Pair[T, U]{First: first, Second: second}
}

// Type inference in use
p := NewPair(1, "hello")  // Pair[int, string] inferred
```

### Type Constraints

```go
// Custom constraints
type Signed interface {
    ~int | ~int8 | ~int16 | ~int32 | ~int64
}

type Unsigned interface {
    ~uint | ~uint8 | ~uint16 | ~uint32 | ~uint64
}

type Integer interface {
    Signed | Unsigned
}

// Tilde (~) allows underlying types
type MyInt int

func Double[T ~int](x T) T {
    return x * 2
}

var mi MyInt = 5
result := Double(mi)  // Works because MyInt's underlying type is int

// Constraint with methods
type Stringer interface {
    String() string
}

func PrintAll[T Stringer](items []T) {
    for _, item := range items {
        fmt.Println(item.String())
    }
}

// Complex constraints
type Number interface {
    ~int | ~int8 | ~int16 | ~int32 | ~int64 |
    ~uint | ~uint8 | ~uint16 | ~uint32 | ~uint64 |
    ~float32 | ~float64
}

type Addable[T any] interface {
    Add(T) T
}

type AddableNumber[T Number] interface {
    Number
    Addable[T]
}
```

## Best Practices Summary

### Code Organization
- Keep packages small and focused
- Use clear, descriptive names
- Group related functionality
- Minimize package dependencies
- Use internal packages for private code

### Error Handling
- Always check errors
- Wrap errors with context
- Use sentinel errors for known conditions
- Create custom error types when needed
- Handle errors at the appropriate level

### Concurrency
- Don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating
- Use channels for coordination
- Keep goroutines simple
- Always handle goroutine cleanup
- Use context for cancellation

### Performance
- Measure before optimizing
- Preallocate slices when size is known
- Use string.Builder for string concatenation
- Be aware of memory allocations
- Profile your code

### Testing
- Write table-driven tests
- Test edge cases
- Use subtests for better organization
- Mock external dependencies
- Aim for high test coverage

### Documentation
- Document all exported items
- Write clear package documentation
- Include examples in documentation
- Keep comments up to date
- Use godoc format

